HEADWORD: Tora
<hw>To"ra</hw> }</mhw> <pr>(?)</pr>,
<pos>n.</pos>; <plu>pl. <plw>Toroth</plw> <pr>(#)</pr></plu>. <ety>[Heb.
<ets>t⟦omac⟧r⟦amac⟧h</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Jewish Lit.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd>
<def>A law; a precept.</def></p>

<p><q>A considerable body of priestly <qex>Toroth</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>S.
R. Driver.</qau></rj></p>

<p><sd>(b)</sd> <def>Divine instruction; revelation.</def></p>

<p><q><qex>Tora</qex>, . . . before the time of Malachi, is generally
used of the revelations of God's will made through the prophets.</q>
<rj><qau>T. K. Cheyne.</qau></rj></p>

<p><sd>(c)</sd> <def>The Pentateuch or ⟦ldquo⟧Law of
Moses.⟦rdquo⟧</def></p>

<p><q>The Hebrew Bible is divided into three parts: (1) The
<qex>Torah</qex>, ⟦ldquo⟧Law,⟦rdquo⟧ or Pentateuch. (2) The Prophets
(Nevi'im in Hebrew) . . . (3) The Kethubim, or the
⟦ldquo⟧Writings,⟦rdquo⟧ generally termed Hagiographa. From the first
letters of these three parts, the word ⟦ldquo⟧Tanakh⟦rdquo⟧ is derived,
and used by Jews as the name of their Bible, the Christian Old
Testament.</q> <rj><qau>C. H. H. Wright.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

